<% text_for :title do %>
  You cannot get a UK visa or electronic travel authorisation (ETA) if you are a dual British or Irish citizen
<% end %>

<% govspeak_for :body do %>
  As a dual citizen, you can travel to the UK using either:

  - a valid UK passport or Irish passport
  - any other valid passport with a ['certificate of entitlement'](/right-of-abode/apply-for-a-certificate-of-entitlement) - this could be digital or a vignette sticker

  ^If you have a digital certificate of entitlement, you must [set up a UKVI account](/evisa/set-up-ukvi-account) and [check your passport details are up to date](/evisa/update-ukvi-account) before you travel.

  ## When you can travel with an expired UK passport
  Your carrier (for example your airline) may allow you to travel if you have both:

  - an expired UK passport, issued in 1989 or later
  - a valid passport for one of the nationalities that can get an [electronic travel authorisation (ETA)](/guidance/check-when-you-can-get-an-electronic-travel-authorisation-eta)

  The personal details on both passports must match.

  It is the carrier's decision whether to allow you to travel.

  If you previously had a UK passport, you can [apply for an emergency travel document](/travel-urgently-from-abroad-without-uk-passport).

  ## If you do not know if you're a British or Irish citizen

  You can check if you're a [British citizen](/check-british-citizenship) or [Irish citizen](https://www.ireland.ie/en/dfa/citizenship/#am-i-an-irish-citizen).

  For example, you may be a British citizen if you were born in the UK or have a British parent.

  ## Apply for a passport or certificate of entitlement
  Find out how to apply for a:

  - [UK passport](/apply-renew-passport)
  - [UK certificate of entitlement](/right-of-abode/apply-for-a-certificate-of-entitlement)
  - [Irish passport](https://www.ireland.ie/en/dfa/passports/passport-online)

  ## What you can do in the UK
  As a British or Irish citizen, you can live, work or study in the UK without a time limit.
<% end %>
